  "beats": [
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "This is Liam, in for Bear. Add an electric field to hydrogen's nondegenerate ground state. Symmetry kills the first-order shift. The second-order shift points down. Try a different perturbation: it still cannot point up.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "props": {
            "command": "Why can the nondegenerate ground state's second-order energy shift never be positive?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — PERTURBATION THEORY",
            "segment": "The Sign of the Second-Order Ground-State Shift",
            "greeting": "Merhaba, Liam",
            "runningText": "checking every virtual coupling…",
            "output": [
              "Squared matrix elements are nonnegative.",
              "Every excited-state denominator is negative."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.27,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "Careful: this is not a claim that every perturbation lowers the full energy. First order may raise it. The narrower puzzle is why the second-order coefficient of a nondegenerate ground state is always zero or negative.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "separate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.54,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "SETUP",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Start with a Hermitian Hamiltonian H zero, a unique ground state, and separated excited levels. Add lambda times H prime, small enough that ordinary nondegenerate perturbation theory applies.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "stack"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.27,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "The second-order coefficient is a sum over every other unperturbed state. Each term is a squared coupling divided by the ground energy minus that state's energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.81,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "The numerator is an absolute square. It can be positive, or exactly zero when the perturbation does not connect those two states. It can never be negative.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "square"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.28,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "The denominator supplies the sign. Every other state lies above a unique ground state, so E zero minus E m is strictly negative for every term in this formula.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.75,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "Nonnegative upstairs, negative downstairs: every contribution is nonpositive. Add the whole column and the answer still cannot cross above zero.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.22,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "ZERO CASE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Why not say always negative? Because a constant perturbation is proportional to the identity. It has no off-diagonal coupling from the ground state, every numerator vanishes, and the second-order shift is exactly zero.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "erase"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.82,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "FIRST ORDER",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "Meanwhile the first-order coefficient is the ground-state expectation of H prime. A positive constant raises the energy linearly even though its second-order coefficient is zero. Do not confuse one coefficient with the full shift.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "branch"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.61,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "EXAMPLE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "For the hydrogen ground state in a weak uniform electric field, parity makes the first-order Stark shift zero. The field mixes in odd-parity excited states, so the surviving second-order terms are negative: the quadratic Stark shift bends downward.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "bend"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.4,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "act": "BOUNDARY",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "If the unperturbed ground energy is degenerate, these denominators can vanish. Then this formula is not the starting point. First diagonalize the perturbation inside the degenerate subspace, then expand the resulting branches.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.16,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "act": "BOUNDARY",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "The statement also assumes the sums or continuum integrals are well defined and the perturbative expansion is valid. Near degeneracy, an unbounded perturbation, or a disappearing bound state can demand more care.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "audit"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.76,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "act": "YOUR TURN",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "Your turn. A unique ground state couples to two excited states. The squared couplings are four and one. The energy denominators are minus two and minus five. What is the second-order coefficient?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "predict"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B13.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.01,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B13.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B14",
      "act": "ANSWER",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "Four divided by minus two is minus two. One divided by minus five is minus zero point two. The sum is minus two point two. Different sizes, same sign logic: it cannot be positive.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "reveal"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B14.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.95,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B14.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T21:14:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B15",
      "act": "OUTRO",
      "estimated_duration_s": 5,
      "narration_text": "Why the Nondegenerate Ground State's Second-Order Shift Is Never Positive.",
